article.description: Lisa Leslie almost single-handedly made sure there wouldn't be another Thursday night, scoring her team's first 13 points of the second half and finishing with 24 as the Los Angeles Sparks defeated the Storm 78-61 in Game 1 of their first-round playoff se
article.headline: Leslie scores 13 straight to open second half

images.name: Leslie_Lisa 020815 inline
images.caption: Lisa Leslie scored her team's first 13 points of the second half.

article.linkText: Leslie's torrid start to second half turns back Storm
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lisa Leslie decided to take the ball hard to the basket even when swarmed by two or three defenders at once.
Thursday, June 27
Los Angeles played with a lot more intensity than it had during the last few games of the regular season. The Sparks' stars also came up big as Lisa Leslie and Mwadi Mabika combined for 47 points.

While Los Angeles struggled a bit tactically on offense in the first half -- the Sparks weren't attacking the basket and failed to get to the foul line even once before the break -- the Sparks were able to break down Seattle's defense. The Storm love to trap, but L.A. did a nice job of moving the ball, using the correct spacing and making the extra pass to beat Seattle's game plan.

Sue Bird and Lauren Jackson were able to combine for 30 points, but didn't get much support from Seattle's role players. No one else on the team scored more than eight points. Kamila Vodichkova didn't score in the first half, Amanda Lassiter failed to give Seattle a lot of points, and if Aida Barnes is going to be a starter, she must give the Storm more than she did Thursday, even if its garbage baskets.

Right now, L.A. has to feel good about going back to the Staples Center.
And she made it look easy. The Los Angeles center scored her team's first 13 points of the second half and finished with 24 as the Sparks defeated the Seattle Storm 78-61 Thursday night in Game 1 of their first-round playoff series. Game 2 of the best-of-three Western Conference series is Saturday in Los Angeles. Leslie still had two straight losses to Seattle fresh in her mind, and almost single-handedly made sure there wouldn't be another. "I decided I had to start scoring over their double- and triple-teams,'' Leslie said. "There was trash-talking on the court, but it was a game we didn't say anything. We let our action speak. ... The situation is, this is the playoffs and we really needed this game.'' These two teams have plenty of history. A fight punctuated one game this season, a 79-60 Seattle win July 11. And back in the 2000 Olympics, Seattle's Lauren Jackson, playing for Australia, pulled out Leslie's hair extension in the gold medal game. This time, the most tense it got was a double-technical in the second half, but there were plenty of hard fouls. Mwadi Mabika scored 14 of her 23 points in the first half and also had seven rebounds and six assists for the defending WNBA champions, who shot a sizzling 61.5 percent in the first half. Tamecka Dixon added 12 points, five rebounds and four assists, and DeLisha Milton had 11 points and six rebounds off the bench. "When they want to play together, they can be the best five in the WNBA,'' Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said of his lineup. Jackson led Seattle with 19 points, and Sue Bird added 11 and eight assists. The Storm are playing in their first postseason since joining the league in 2000. Following back-to-back losses to Houston, they won seven of their last nine to reach the playoffs. Jackson acknowledged that the Sparks' playoff experience is an advantage, but stressed it doesn't mean that much. "What is playoff experience anyway,'' she said. "It's just another game. In 20 years' time, who's going to remember this game? Nobody.'' Seattle pulled within 46-43 on a basket by Jackson with 15:05 left, then the Sparks went on a 20-4 run to pull away. "Our team didn't realize they were going to start defending their championship tonight,'' Storm coach Lin Dunn said. "I think we got a good lesson tonight.'' Cooper came into the game saying his team had to show more effort in the playoffs than it did during the season against Seattle. And the Sparks seemed to find an answer whenever the Storm threatened. "We kept working and didn't get outhustled,'' he said. When Bird pulled Seattle within four points late in the first half on a 3-pointer, Mabika answered with a 3 of her own that helped the Sparks take a 37-30 lead into halftime. "It's just the confidence that we've been there before and know what it takes to get the lead and keep the lead,'' Mabika said. A short jumper by Seattle's Adia Barnes that appeared to beat the halftime buzzer was waved off by the referees, prompting Storm owner and Starbucks Coffee Co. chairman Howard Schultz to jump out of his front-row seat and yell profanities from on the court. As the officials exited at halftime, Schultz approached them to express his anger with the call. Mabika made her first five shots, and the Sparks connected on seven of their first eight. Seattle was held to 35 percent shooting, to Los Angeles' 56 percent. The Sparks held a 33-23 rebounding edge, with Leslie pulling down nine. "We can only go up from here,'' Bird said.
